<h2 id="the-process">The process</h2>
<p>Iâ€™m an early riser. Thereâ€™s nothing better than waking way before the sunâ€”before the kids need to be packed up for school and before responsibilities take overâ€”and starting the day with a text editor and a hot cup of coffee.</p>

<p>I start writing at 5:30 each morning, and plug away until 6:50 when the kids arise. I donâ€™t always fill that time with writingâ€”sometimes I need to stare at my outline a bit and orient my current thoughts within the larger story Iâ€™m telling. Sometimes I noodle on the right word choice or the best phrase for a solid hour. But it doesnâ€™t matterâ€”itâ€™s my time and my words.</p>

<p>Iâ€™ve been thinking about this topic for a few years now, which has manifested as a couple of conference talks, lots of conversations with allies in the industry, a whole lot of affinity mapping, and finally as a book outline. To be honest, Iâ€™m a better outliner than mapper, and feel like affinity mapping took me too far afield. Something about a nested list of words clarifies everything for me in a way that a cluster of notes doesnâ€™t.</p>

<p>I use the Bear notes app to write, and I keep my outline in a window on the left half of my screen, with my current chapter in a separate window on the right. If I keep the outline visible at all times, it both keeps me on track and reassures me when I have moments of â€œWTF are you even doing, Bernstein?â€</p>

